My friend Alex Preston was a freelance designer who lived with severe food allergies and medical conditions all his life.

He managed the best he could until he got so sick he was bed ridden in the hospital. What he does next is truly inspiring and a lesson for us all.

What obstacles have you had to overcome? What lesson did you learn?

Who can you trust? How to avoid fake gurus and what Mike Winnet calls “contrepreneurs”. They all follow a very specific formula to sell you a pipe dream—

You don’t need any special skill. You don’t need to posses any talent. Anybody can do it. It requires no money and little work and you can do it from anywhere by doing this one thing. Sigh.

Recently I was on the Millionaire Secrets podcast with @jefflernerofficial. We got into a fascinating and critical discussion as to why most creatives, designers (and entrepreneurs in general) will always struggle...
​​
​​...and never truly hit the big time. You can watch the full video on Jeff’s YouTube channel or on his podcast. Link in bio.

node.text:
The reason why we don’t share our story is because we aren’t very good at recognizing our own unique gifts and talents.

We let the fear of disappointing someone that holds great emotional power over us, prevent us from doing exactly what we need to do. I want to encourage you to step into the light and shine on. The world is waiting. Parts of this story was inspired by @matt_essam (who I’m happy to learn from).

In case you haven’t seen this video on our Youtube channel, I want to share it with you here. In this short clip (1/4) I talk about why carousels are so important to getting organic growth on Instagram.

As more companies establish viable social networks, we are going to see an increase in value of creators as they compete against one another for exclusive content from popular creators.

Joe Rogan recently signed an exclusive distribution agreement with Spotify for $100m. This and deals like the one with Ninja are a sign of things to come.

node.text:
Just wanted to give you a peek into my world and include a few of the books that help to shape my thinking. Now before your head explodes, I have not read all of the books. Not even close.

If it’s a good month for me, I’ll read 3-5 books, which works out to be about 48 books a year.

It’s not about consumption. It’s about retention. It’s not about retention, it’s about application. So it’s better to read 1 book and apply what you learn than to read all the books and do nothing.

About the space…
It’s a fairly tight room considering how much content I create which includes: YouTube, Clubhouse, Twitter, Instagram, LinkedIn, Futur Pro Zoom calls, virtual talks and podcasts. Everything here is either essential for work or makes me happy.

What’s one thing you do or have that makes you feel more creative?

Asgard is not a place, it’s a people. One last look at our studio space. We just handed the keys to the new tenant and I said my final goodbye to our home for the last 13 years.

Looking back, I remember the feeling of panic when we purchased this building back in 2007. Did we bite off more than we can chew? 12k square feet in prime realestate in Santa Monica. It was the biggest challenge I had taken on at that time. And I wasn’t sure if we could manage the payments.

Now, we prepare our new studio for the next chapter in the story of The Futur.

“People don’t buy what you do, they buy why you do it.”—Simon Sinek.

People no longer buy products, they join tribes. They’re searching for meaning and identity. — Marty Neumeier.

Today’s guest post is by @justcreative . Follow them for more tips like this.

The Futur’s purpose—disrupt education industry. Our mission: teach 1 billion people how to make a living doing what they love. The vision: distributed, scalable, and affordable educational content.

It’s private art school without the crippling debt. We are clear who we are and who we serve. Are you clear in your purpose and mission?

node.text:
Probably one of my favorite books on life and business is 7 Strategies for Wealth and Happiness. It’s written by Jim Rohn who has influenced many of the greats including Tony Robbins, Brian Tracy and Darren Hardy.

When I spoke to author Austin Kleon, he said, “Trace ideas back to their source.” It’s like genealogy but for ideas. As far as I can tell, this is the source.

Today’s guest post is by @6posters. Follow them for more content like this.
